The initial decade data is missing a fair amount of data. I'd like to try and see if the trend method for imputation will work for any of these. To make this quicker, I'll set up my trend line prediction in a function.

In [213]:
def predict_by_trend(column_name, numVals):
    years = pd.Series(garbage.index).iloc[numVals:]
    values = garbage[column_name].iloc[numVals:]
    years_reshaped = years.values.reshape(-1, 1) #to run regression, my X has to be 2D
    lr = LinearRegression()
    lr.fit(years_reshaped, values)
    #now use lr to predict first numVals values
    missing_years = pd.Series(garbage.index).iloc[:numVals]
    missing_years_reshaped = missing_years.values.reshape(-1,1)
    predicted_values = lr.predict(missing_years_reshaped)
    return predicted_values

Based on this initial look at the data, I think this is my idea for imputation: Fill data in using the trend line. Replace any negative values with the next non-negative value in the column. This seems to make the most sense for this data in this time series.

In [215]:
def replace_negatives (df, col_name):
    for i in range (0, len(df[col_name])):
        if (df[col_name].iloc[i] < 0):
            #find next positive value in the column
            next_positive_value = next((val for val in df[col_name][i:] if val > 0), None)
            if (next_positive_value is not None):
                df[col_name].iloc[i] = next_positive_value

Showstopper: I spent so much time reading about and asking questions about the unfamiliar parts of my garbage data (which was the categories) that I failed to carefully look at the part of the data that seemed the clear part (the years). I took at face value that the EPA dataset included Solid Waste Data from 1960 to 2018. It wasn't until many hours spent on this data as well as population and economy data that I realized the insurmountable problem with this dataset: they did include data from the years 1960 to 2018 but not complete data. They only report the data every decade until 1990, then every 5 years until 2010. This will not work for a predictive model. There are only 8 recessionary periods from 1960 to 2018. One of those starts in 1969. Even assuming garbage could be predictive of the business cycle, a model can't predict the start of a recession in 1969 if the most recent garbage data is from 1960. So, I'm back to the drawing board. This is frustrating, but I feel like it may be the most valuable thing I will learn from this project. Data is and always will be the crux of all machine learning and data isn't easy. It isn't easy to obtain, to understand, or to manipulate. And once you do, there are limitations due to the simplifications you've necessarily had to make. I've reached out to my Waste Management Professional friend to see what contacts she has to be able to obtain data. In the meantime, the second best dataset I've been able to find is produced by the state of Washington. They break down their Solid Waste produced by category by year from 2000 to 2021. This is a very small dataset. For purposes of learning and completion of this project I am going to push ahead with this small dataset hoping that my friend will be able to track down a larger dataset for me.¶

Analysis 1: PCA¶

I'm going to perform Principle Component Analysis on my data to glean further information about it.

PCA for Feature Selection¶

In [240]:
# Do I need to standardize? All my data is in "short tons" so it's the same scale. However, the range does vary widely. I will scale so that
#I don't have some features take over based only on their larger numbers
X_std = StandardScaler().fit_transform(garbage_clean)
# Create a PCA instance: pca
pca = PCA()
principalComponents = pca.fit_transform(X_std)
# Plot the explained variances
features = range(pca.n_components_)
plt.bar(features, pca.explained_variance_ratio_, color='black')
plt.xlabel('PCA features')
plt.ylabel('variance %')
plt.xticks(features)
# Save components to a DataFrame
PCA_components = pd.DataFrame(principalComponents)

This shows me that most of the variation in my data can be explained by a single PCA feature. This single PCA feature is a linear combination of my 61 features. This tells me that most of the variation in my data can be accounted for in a single way of combining my features. I think that over all, it tells me that my features are pretty highly correlated. This makes sense. When one category of garbage goes up, its likely that garbage production overall is going up and so other garbage categories are also going up. Plus, this data hasn't been normalized by population, so as the population has increased over the decades, all garbage categories would be increasing. This reminds me that I need to go back and normalize my data based on population. I may want to use this PCA feature 1 as my only feature in a model, since it's a combination of the most variable of my features.

I must be not understanding how this works. If I had run the data from our previous Linear Regression assignment through a linear regression model (this time with all the data, no test split out), could it perfectly predict every y value? I know I would expect overfitting, but perfect fitting? All I'm doing is picturing the 4 points my linear algebra teacher gave us when we were learning how to use projection to do Least Squares. From a ML model point of view, we can see that with such a small dataset the model is essentially able to "memorize" the variablility of the data (again, how does it do this within the constraints of a linear system?). I think it just showed me that I don't understand Linear Regression models like I need to.

These are the full names of the columns that were highly correlated with the change in the unemployment rate. The first five are negatively correlated, the last five are positive. For all my tinkering, this may be the first real insight I've found in my data. It's interesting to consider what people throw away more when feeling economic instability versus what they throw away less. It appears people throw away less: plastic bottles, containers, small appliances, paper plates, and clothing. During times of unemployment do people tend to purchase fewer things in bottles? One easy way to cut back is to not buy water in plastic bottles. I would assume they buy less over all which is why containers would be going down. They would not be replacing their small appliances during that time. It's easy to cut paper plates out of the budget by using regular plates when trying to cut back and it's easy to not purchase new clothes, but continue to wear the old ones.

Why would the last five be positively correlated? Paper, Cans, newspapers, glass jars, Other paperboard. I have no conjectures on the paper, but the cans and glass jars could indicate people eating food that has been stored (rather than out in restaurants or fresh food) during times of economic downturn. I already conjectured on the newspapers.

The graphs really shows an amazing picture! (And way more information that the metric does). This model may not be able to predict the exact amount that unemployment will spike but from 1980 on, it predicted each spike that would happen. Overall, I believe garbage data has the potential to have a number of predictive abilities when it comes to economic values. I've seen evidence of moderate to strong correlation with some of the data. With imputed data, I was able to train some models that could mimic the trend of the unemployment rate. I feel like the data I have to work with is insufficient to make stronger claims, but I believe this area of study warrants further exploration.
